author: servicemeson

title: Fully Customisable replacement watch strap keeper

description.text:
Disclaimer: All watches are different.Be sure to check your watches dimension

This is a replacement watch strap keeper for your cheap watches. All my (unexpensive) watches have broken this way so I made a universal solution. You need to print in a FLEXIBLE filament of any sort, but it does not need to be super flexible like ninja flex, it just needs to be able to stretch abit.

The measurements need to be measured according to the size of your watch and the tolerance of your printer, so you probably need a vernier caliper unless you want to approximate it. Ensure that the wall thickness is higher than the original strap as depending on what material the layer adhesion will be different.

If you decide to print with text, print the text side facedown. Depending on your printer and build surface, you might want to use a raft and/or supports. Otherwise, this should not be too demanding on your printer(flexible filament aside).

Leave suggestions in the comments, I will improve it when I am free.

Edit: thanks to user WrinklyWink for informing me of the proper name.

Build a name plate with any text!
OpenSCAD script allowing you to define the text and the script will generate a nametag.

• Download and unzip Nameplate.zip
  • Run Nameplate.scad and change the 'text' variable
  • Consider some of the other vars if needed
  • Export to STL, slice and print.
  • Have a cold beer.
    • TL;DR: Run Nameplate.stl and change the text, Export, Slice and print! Rookie Mistake #1: Ensure you have the most recent version of OpenSCAD. Rookie Mistake #2: This print will not work unless you are drinking a beer. This script uses the excellent Write.scad script written by HarlanDMii. Much kudos to him! You need Write.scad installed, I have included it in Nameplate.zip for your convenience. Of course, if you already have it installed, then the Nameplate.scad file is all you need. http://www.3dfuture.com.au/2012/01/3d-printed-nameplate-generator/

comments.text: Great little script. I've made a small amendment to it to allow generating the box only or the letters only. I haven't tried a print but the theory is that you can then print the letters in a different colour to the plate. You would then have to stick the letters onto the plate. If anyone is interested I can share it as a derivative.

title: 2 in 1 spinner, spin coater and magnetic stirrer from HDD
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Using parts from HDD, I have created a spinner that spins a disk, coating PCBs or other flat things in a somewhat even coat of liquid. It is also can be used as a magnetic stirrer by using the magnet from the HDD. The unit uses the brushless motor from HDD to spin the disk. Since the unit does not need to have a lot of torque, this motor is perfect as it can spin at high speeds (depends on the motor driver and HDD type).
It can be used for different purpose, it is just depended on the disk.
Coating stainless steel did not work well but looks cool. Coating silicon wafers work well (if the wafer can fit) because of the smoothness of the surface

Project link: http://tinkersprojects.com/Projects/2-in-1-spinner-from-hdd/

Parts list:

  1. HDD brushless motor (assuming it's the same dimensions as mine)
  2. Motor controller (http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/SUPPO-50A-brushless-motor-speed-controller-/282089041823?hash=item41add12f9f:g:WjcAAOSw3xJVYrya)
  3. PLEX control unit (see http://plexcontroller.com)
  4. power plug (trying to find where I got them from)

with the motor controller, if the motor runs for too long then the motor controller will need a bigger heatsink to help it stay cool and not melt the case. I have not put any air hole in the case or put and heat sink on due to I'm not running it for too long at a time.

title: Vive Lighthouse Gun Stock (Nerf Adapter)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Shoulder Stock for Vive Lighthouse controllers

two halves will be screwed in the hole in the controller from top and bottom to fix the controller, sensors won't be obstructed by this.

you need a nerf gun shoulder stock (nearly every one will work) and a nerf retaliator stock extender, either http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:117824, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:164845 or http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:160925 to complete this.

you can choose between a 80mm long back part and a 120mm long one, depending on your preferences.

Vitamins needed:
4x M3 Nut
4x M3 Washer
4x M3 Screw (length from 6 to 15mm is fine)
1x M4 Screw (length minimum 35mm)
1x M4 Nut
1x M6 Screw (length minimum 30mm)
1x M6 Nut
2x M6 Washer

No support needed, parts are oriented as they should be printed, hole bridging is built into the parts where needed

Assembly:

  • Print all Parts, sand down the pins on the svivel part so they will flush fit in the top part of the two halves, drill away hole bridging, drill the holes in the back part so M3 screws can pass throuigh (they are intentionally too small, why - see below)
  • Drill holes into the nerf retaliator stock extender so they match the back part of the stock
  • put M3 nuts in the polygon holes in the back part and slide it into the nerf retaliator stock extender, screw in M3 screws
    (Alternative: just use wood screws and screw them through the stock extender into the back part, in that case don't drill the holes, this will be faster and easier but you cant disassemble it many times)
  • Put the top half and bottom half into your controller, insert the svivel part in the top part and screw everything together, make sure you have everything facing the right way so the sensors won't be obnstructed, screw it tight, no worries the controllers can take quite a lot of pressure force
  • screw the controller to the back part, adjust the angle to your liking and pull the screw tight (M6, nut and washers)

I strongly advise you use your shoulder stock "upside down" - see pictures - that way you wont hit the stock with your headset when aiming down sights

you can always leave the two halves and the svivel part screwed into the controller as they won't interfere with the sensors

comments.text: In fact, the lighthouse system needs only around four sensors hit to calculate it's position whereas the controller has about 20, so they're designed to work even when obstructed. I made sure I cover no sensors with my design (even that wouldn't be too much of a problem), so the tracking is not harder then when obstructed by your other hand or your head for instance. It's very unlikely that you obstruct this gun mount with your other hand or head (as one tends to do often when just using the regular controllers) because you will be holding it against your shoulder most of the time and so your other hand and head will be out of the way.

title: IBOT Vr2.0 - The Simple Robot Model Kit

description.text:
IBOT is the graceful successor to the original design. I took the proportions and style from Vr1 and expanded on every aspect of the 3d model. So whats new?

  • Articulated ball joints for the arms and legs.
  • Pivot joints for the elbows and knees
  • Improved details
  • Functional Hands to accommodate accessories.
  • Efficient modelling techniques (all pieces are designed with a flat face for easy printing & small parts ensure it can be printed on the tiniest of print beds)

I've put alot of love into this design and i hope it shows through. It's a great little weekend project and i'd love to see how you make it your own.

Make sure to tag me on instagram if you make your own IBOT @lew_j. I'd love to see what colours/materials/finishes you've used!

Printer:

M3D Micro

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 Microns

Infill:

Non

Notes:

Total Print Time for IBOT Alone - 15hr
Total Print Time for all pieces - 20hr

I personally used the following settings on all pieces.

Supports? only on Hands, Body, Pelvis
Rafts? Recommended
Infill? All pieces are hollow with the thick walls setting enabled
Resolution? I printed at 0.2mm layer thickness (200 microns)

Some light sanding maybe required depending on the resolution you use.

The ball joints are a tight but trust me they do fit.

IBOT is approximately 14cm tall when complete.

Instructions
  1. Print all pieces and remove excess support material / imperfections
  2. Slot two ball pegs into the body.
  3. Insert Pelvis into flat end of the body (and Glue if required)
  4. Slot two ball pegs into the Pelvis
  5. Attach Biceps & Femurs to the relevant Ball Joints
  6. Attach Feet & Forearms to the relevant Pivot Joints
  7. Plug the Hands into the Forearms
  8. Slot in the Head.

Enjoy!

How I Designed This.

IBOT was designed & exported in Lightwave 3D. I used basic geometry to create each piece and added the necessary sockets/joints for articulation. This was mainly achieved by trial & error. I noticed you need a 0.1mm gap between a ball and its socket to make a decent friction fit. This also applies to the pivot joints & Head which rely on friction to move/stay in place. I used Rigidink PLA Filament which i wholeheartedly recommend to anyone.

title: Antweight Robotwars Firestorm R/C Robot
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
An antweight version of our Robotwars robot, Firestorm.

The dimensions are a little off, but overall I'm happy enough with it. My version is printed in Colorfabb XT yellow, now it just needs a sweet paint job on the back to finish it off (or I complete my Bigbox upgrade to dual nozzles).

You'll need a bunch of other parts they should be less than £50 and can be reused in other tiny robots, see below for details.

Printer:

BigBox3d

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.25mm

Infill:

20-100%

Notes:

So you should be able to use pretty much any filament for most parts and any layer height between 0.1 to 0.25mm. The parts should be easy prints, there are no large overhangs, and the parts have nice large contact patches.

The lid should probably be printed in something a little flexible as it needs to be bent to fit on top, but it has a cutout so even really stiff PLA should work without snapping.

The tyres should be printed in Ninjaflex or other rubbery TPU, although you could get away with just using a couple of appropriately sized o-rings or superglue-ing some strips of rubber band instead.

You need one of each part, other than the wheels and tyres where, obviously you need 2 of each.

Bits you will need
  • 180maH 2S battery
  • 2 x 9g HXT900 Servos for drive
  • 1 x 9g 90 degree metal gear servo
  • 1 x BEC This one looks good, I'm currently using an old ESC for a 5V supply, should be much better with 6V from this supply
  • Assorted heat shrink tubing
  • Some 3mm cable ties
  • 4 small (1/8w or less is fine, you can even use surface mount ones if your soldering skills are up to the job) 1k-10k resistors the value doesn't matter too much as long as all 4 are the same value. For better centering you can match the resistors into identical pairs
  • 4 x M2 x 5mm countersunk screws (for attaching the lid, search ebay, still waiting for these myself)
  • A paper clip or other thin bendable metal (for flipper hinges)
  • A few cm of 1mm round elastic cord (for returning the flipper, search google/ebay etc)
  • Some thick elastic bands or some o-rings 20-23mm internal diameter (if you're not printing tyres)

If you've already got some radio gear (I have an older Turnigy 9x with FrSky modules) you might be able to use that otherwise you'll need:

Cheap option:

  • 1 x Tx and Rx Seems to have mixing on board, but due to right angled plugs on the receiver, you'd probably need to solder servos and BEC directly to it to make it all fit in the shell, which might not be a problem as it is very cheap!

OR

More expensive option:

  • 1 x Tx and Rx Plugs on the receiver should be usable as they are parallel to the pcb

Even more expensive:
Buy separate micro receiver, handset and transmitter module

Modification to servos

You will need to modify the 2 drive servos for continuous rotation and, optionally, modify them for a bit more speed.

Dismantle the servo

  • Remove the 4 screws on the bottom of the servo
  • Pull the top and bottom covers off the body of the servo

Electrical modification

  • Cut the wires going to the potentiometer at the potentiometer end, so you have 3 free wires coming from the pcb
  • Solder a resistor between each of the end wires and the center wire
  • Insulate it all, I prefer heatshrink to tape as insulating tape tends to leave a mess if you need to get back into it for repairs/changes
  • The PCB and new resistors will probably have to sit outside the servo with the motor wires running back through the hole where the receiver wire was running previously.

Mechanical modification (continuous rotation)

  • The gears should be removed from the top of the servo
  • Clip the plastic stop from under the top gear
  • You may also want to carefully drill out the top gear so it freely rotates on the d shaped shaft of the potentiometer (if you don't do this the servo still has sufficient torque to turn the gear on the D shaped shaft and will do this drilling for you. If you are also doing the speed mod, you should definitely drill out the top gear as increasing the speed reduces the torque quite substantially)

Optional Mechanical modification (speed increase)

  • To do this you need to remove a stage in the gear train
  • The top gear on the center shaft should be removed
  • Clean the oil/grease off gears of the potentiometer shaft, to make the superglue bond better
  • Superglue the top and bottom gears of the potentiometer shaft, together.
  • Take care to glue only the gears on the potentiometer shaft to each other and not to the potentiometer or the gear on the centre shaft
  • Reassemble the gear train without the the top gear of the centre shaft.

Screw the drive servos back together

Put it all together
  • You'll need to trim the mounting lugs off the flipper servo
  • Put the tyres on your wheels
  • Push the wheels onto the drive servos, fix with the screws supplied with the servo
  • Cable tie your drive servos in place, see below
  • Slide the battery in-between the drive servos with the wires exiting towards the front
  • The BEC should fit on the left front of the robot, cable tie loosely in place until you've got all your wiring sorted out
  • The flipper hinges are created by passing a short length (15-20mm or so) of the unfolded paper clip through the holes in the flipper and lower body, on each side, bend the ends to stop the clips coming out.
  • For fitting the flipper arm, you'll need to power on the servo with the receiver so you can find the limits
  • The receiver may need to be uncased and should sit just over the drive servos and battery.
  • The elastic should be tied around the end of the arm (the hole in the arm is a red herring, sorry) and through the hole in the flipper. It should be fairly slack at full extension and tighter when folded away.
  • Routing cables can be tricky, I found pushing spare loops into heat shrink made it easier, although you may want to cut and solder your cables to the perfect length once you've test fit everything.
Servo placement
Created with OpenSCAD, the lower shell is a whole load of horrid polyhedron blocks.

description.text: These are a Left and Right tslot fan shroud with seats for 2 3mm led bulbs design I remixed for http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1650591. They are a tooless option for mounting 40mm fans. Still working on clearances for the leds and the best way to route the wires out of the shroud. I am planning to run all 4 leds in parallel and connect them to the ramps board with the same pins that power the board cooling fan. I will wire both part cooling fans in parallel and have only 1 set of red/black wires going to the board. fit checked the clearances with the tslots on the carriage and there is nor problem and did not require post processing.

title: Shuttle R.I.P.

description.text:
This is a sculpture from my recent solo show, "Tomorrow Land"! You can read all about the meaning of the work here: rhgallery.com/site/exhibitions/tomorrowland/tomorrowland_pressrelease.pdf
This sculpture commemorates the end of the shuttle program.  The shuttle silhouette is cut out of a cemetery.  Pour one out for this retired work-horse!
It's art so it's not "for" anything other than to impress your friends with your well-developed cultural palette.

Print at the highest resolution your printer can muster! I printed this for my show at .22mm.
I recommend the Natural ABS color because it looks the most high-end.

comments.text: By the way, we printed the "muffin top" version of this piece (just the top chunk) at the Affordable Art Fair in LA on a Replicator and audiences had a great time watching the cemetery scene rising quickly up from the build platform.

Prototype Prints

A number of prototype prints to measure the size of different bottle openings

First ideas including the concept, design, and then I started to get measurements I measured a bottle cap and then reduced the size on the bottom then the top. I did this so the stopper could fit in different sized bottle openings. Prototype 1 - Used a cone shape then sliced the cone to the correct diameter After a number of attempts I found the correct shape, size, and depth I wanted to use. Final adjustments were made to make the stopper look better. I imported a jet design from the inbuilt library on 123D Design. A simple design was created by combining triangles Another simple design was created by putting cubes on top of each other, and by reducing their scale each level.

Bottle Stopper

Overview & Background:

To design and create a shape or object to put on top of a bottle stopper. Students will learn how to design simple shapes/designs in Autodesk 123D Design software or any another preferred CAD software.

2.) Give each person the "Stopper V1" STL file, and drag and drop the file into a new file.

3.) Design a shape or object on top of the stopper.

4.) Each person to show their finished design.

1 hour - 3 hours (depending on how good you want the designs to be)

Students should have designed a shape or object that can be printed on top of the stopper.

title: NinjaFlex / Flexible PLA Working robotic hand using 9g servos

description.text:
This is a working robotic hand. You need to print the fingers with a flexible filament like NinjaFlex or any sort of TPU or Flexible plastic. The palm and thumb adapter should be printed in PLA/ABS/your regular plastic of choice. I used the Flexible PLA from hobbyking. To make the fingers move, you need to attach a cord (fishing line/thin wire) to the top of the finger and push it to the palm where you will attach it to a 9g servo motor (like tg9e). Each finger has a dedicated servo motor, and all 5 of them are located on the back of the palm. You must be careful to install them in the right order so they don't block the installation of the next one. You also need to insert a rod, 4mm in diameter, through the 4 fingers on the front. The thumb is mounted using the adjustable adapter, allowing you to adjust the angle at which it will operate. You will need a few M3, M4 and M8 bolts and nuts.

Concerning electronics, there are many great tutorials on instructables.com about how to make hands like this work with PC or with a dedicated sensor glove. I designed this hand because most of the instructables require a lot of assembly and don't last very long. They stay in the bent position after afew bendings, whereas the 3d printed parts always tend to return to it's original form, depending on the material.

This Moineau (a.k.a. "progressing cavity") pump can be used for many purposes, like the original, when volumetric pumping is needed.
We are currently testing our crazy idea for a modified extruder, allowing a 3D printer to be fed with plastic pellets instead of filament, and this type of "screw" is the only one that can provide a precise feed of plastic (Auger screws cannot do this).
NOTE: version 11 has been updated, some of the previous ones had bugs and/or the resulting STLs wouldn't work, please use the current one that is improved and will render correct STL files for values of "number of lobes" from 2 to 9.

description.text:
Use this customizable clamp to mount your smartphone on the air frame of your car.

Just measure or google the thickness and width of your smartphone and put them into the customizer app. Take into account the extra thickness or width when using a smartphone cover.
Most air frames are oriented horizontally, but if the air frame of your car is rotated at a certain angle, then you can rotate the clamp to keep your smartphone horizontal.

The clamp is easy to print and does not require any support.

To use it, just slide your smartphone sideways into the clamp, and then mount the clamp on your air frame. Make sure your smartphone fits tightly in the bracket (it shouldn't be able to move around). The clamp should also fit tightly on the air frame. If this isn't the case, better print a new clamp.

That's it! enjoy!

update 17/07/2016:

  • Just wanted to say thanks to anyone who has liked, collected, downloaded and/or printed the model. It makes me feel good to know that this is something which is useful for a lot of people.
  • I highly recommend printing this model in ABS. If you print it in PLA and leave it on the air frame for days, it will deform and loose it's clamping force. Also, when printed in PLA, do not turn on the heath because the clamp will deform!
  • Apparently, using values like 70.00 and 70. generate errors in customizer (but not in openscad). I added a note in the code to remind users of this.

print_settings.Notes:: Print it flat on its back (pins up) for easier printing. The bearing cap has an overhang, but if you just print in mid air it will eventually recover and you can just file off the dangling loops. Or use supports - it will make it a little prettier, but also more plastic and time.

description.text:
The split pins on fixitnate's version has a problem with snapping - likely a combination of direction of print and the fact that only the top half of the pin holds the weight of the spool. This version has a solid pin to try to add a little extra strength at the expense of the superior retention of the split pin. These won't fall off in normal use, but the bearings are able to pull off more easily (one kept falling off while I was trying to snap it on the rail).The upside is that these can be used with a more rigid plastic without cracking the pins.

This design is fully compatible with the Rollin on 20s roller (bearings are slightly lower, but the spacing is about the same) so if you can print it as a replacement for just one side if you have a cracked pin.

SolidPin-Snug hasn't been tested, but it's not a vast deviation from the "bit of tolerance" version, which was printed (and I'm using). The only difference is I added 0.2mm of plastic to the top of the clip (taking it from a technically perfect 7mm down to 6.8mm space) and I added a chamfer to the inside corner of the clip bits that grab the 2020 rail and give a slightly stronger pinch, which with any luck should wear down a little to fit perfectly. A little file work can fix it if I am wrong. I'll try printing this when I get the chance, but right now I have two rollers that work and a spare already, so I'm going to call it. I'm leaving the other ones because you may not be the adventurous type, in which case you can print one that there is proof it works and fix it. I'll remove the lesser versions if/when I test the theoretically better one. I've also included the Fusion 360 file in case anyone wants to take a crack at it themselves. You just have to promise not to judge me for my terrible CAD skillz when you see how I made it.

The "bit of tolerance" version works almost perfectly. The 2020 clip is a little loose, allowing it to slide freely, which could be a problem. 3-4 layers of painters tape on the top of the rail helps. Alternatively you could wrap a rubber band around the two rollers (above the rail, below the plate) and just use the spool to hold them apart, but that may cause too much friction with the spool on the edge of the pin plate. if you print without supports you will need to remove a few loops of material where the bearing goes, but with a little force the bearing snaps on, and isn't prone to coming off by accident. The clip goes on the rail with a little effort, even if it is a little loosey-goosey once it's on.

This "too tight" version has -no- wiggle room. You will need a file or sandpaper to make this fit anything. I will fix that soon. For now, you will need to remove some plastic from the bearing retention disk, a little from the bearing shaft, and a lot from the 2020 clip part (the bit that has to go over the top of the 2020, but inside the edge of it). Rounding it a bit helped, and printing at a lower infill with fewer side perimeters would also help (increase the springability of the clip). The upside is this allows you to get a perfect fit, if you have a lot of patience and some good needle files. The 2020 clip is still loose though.

Printer:

Folger Tech Kossel revB

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

20% Rectilinear

Notes:

Infill is likely unimportant, and as long as you have solid surfaces you should be good. Fewer vertical walls (I did two, and it clipped on perfectly) and less infill makes it easier to get the clip over the rail. I doubt doing higher infill would make much of a difference for the function (it's pretty solid).

No feature is very small, so resolution is extremely unimportant. I predict anything up to, and including a 1mm resolution would print this well enough to be used. It may not be pretty at that size, but how pretty does it need to be?

Print it flat on its back (pins up) for easier printing. The bearing cap has an overhang, but if you just print in mid air it will eventually recover and you can just file off the dangling loops. Or use supports - it will make it a little prettier, but also more plastic and time.

remixed_from.author: adafruit
remixed_from.title: PiGRRL Zero Raspberry Pi Zero Gameboy

description.text:
I really liked the idea of the PiGRRL Zero but I wasn't keen on the case at all so I decided to remix it into something a little more to my taste... which may have been ambitious given I only got my first 3D printer a few weeks earlier.

This isn't a professional job by any means and I'm sure more experienced makers could improve it dramatically, but it does serve the purpose for which it was intended, so I'm happy with it and will be unlikely to make any further changes to the uploaded design.

Internally I use the same parts as the PiGRRL with the exception of the battery of which I used one which I had spare already.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QdQ0XkW3DVg

Printer:

Da Vinci Jr

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The top and bottom were printed without rafts and supports and came out fine.
The triggers will require support at the retaining ring sits below the main body of the trigger.

Note that the positioning of the trigger is important as it rests against the microswitch which must seated accordingly.

There is a cut out at the foot of the bottom section as I had a multi-colour LED that I wanted to incorporate into the design. This is not required for a build.

Finally, for power you will need a slim-fit Micro USB as the powerboost is recessed and the aperture is quite small.This was because I had a flat-style cable that I wanted to use. You could always increase the width in your design software of choice.

I created a entirely new case in Tinkercad starting with a basic rectangle and two half spheres. This was then sliced and hollowed.

I brought in the screw posts from the original design and seated them accordingly - after all there is no point it reinventing the wheel. I also used the buttons and d-pad from the PiGRRL Zero.

description.text:
Summary

Dyson like bladeless fan, Version 2!
Uses a custom designed impeller to move the air instead of a normal fan.
Airflow is much higher on this Version 2.

Things you'll need:

  • Filament
  • RS-380 motor (Don't use this motor higher than 10K RPM!)
    http://www.ebay.com/itm/MABUCHI-RS-380PH-4045-DC3V-12V-6V-7-2V-16200RPM-High-Speed-Carbon-Brush-DC-Motor-/262570016882
  • PWM speed controller
    http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/12V-36V-Pulse-Width-PWM-DC-Motor-Speed-Controller-Regulator-Switch-12V-24V-3A-/191784615003
  • 2x 624 Bearing
    http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/10-PCS-Miniature-Rubber-Sealed-Metal-Shielded-Metric-Radial-Ball-Bearing-Model-/400458020258
  • 4x ISO4762 or ISO4014 M4 x 10 bolt
  • 4x M4 nut

Optional Things:

  • A metal shaft, see in pictures. (A normal 3D-printed shaft will work fine but a metal, turned shaft reduces vibration and noise.)
  • Dust filter or fine mesh so the impeller doesn't clog up over time.
  • Rubber feet

Assembly Instructions:

Download the Assembly manual here:
http://helixmedia.pe.hu/BFV2Download.php


Updates:
20-3-2017: Updated eBay RS-380 motor link. (eBay seller changed link)
19-7-2016: Updated the 'ShaftCoupling' and added 'Impeller-Cap'.
23-7-2016: Uploaded Assembly manual.



This version is not scalable. If you need a scalable fan, check out the Version 1. (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1645081)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

8

i don't get the point of using 2 bearings??? why not use only 1 bearing inside the impeller itself, and have the coupling be a stationary pole?
the pole connecting it doesn't need to spin, so you don't need a second bearing all the way at the bottom....
i can imagine the use of 2 bearings will introduce extra slack in the design, which might be the cause of vibrations, and thus the noise....
get rid of the bottom bearing, use a stationary rod instead, and it won't vibrate, so less noise...﻿
comments.author: Efari

comments.text: Double bearing is here to prevent if one fails, it won’t blow up the entire bottom ;)
comments.author: Efari

comments.text: While the logic makes sense, it is definitely not the best way to add this safety feature. I'll be adding a remix with my solution. Basically it will just be a post with a bottom diameter that matches the bearing so that you can press it into the bottom bearing slot. This way, the post doesn't spin during normal operation, reducing possible vibration noise. If the bearing does fail, then the weakest point will be the press fit of the shaft into the base, and this will simply slip and start spinning, ensuring the only damage that may occur will be to this small printed post, which is a quick replacement.

comments.text:
reason it is called bladeless, is it does not have fan blades, instead it has the impeller...
The impeller does have some small blades, but the trick is that the impeller moved air out alongside the ring, and the movement of this "ringformet air movement" pulls the air inside the ring, with it, and therefore, even though the impellar only moves lets say, one m3 of air, the totail air movement is alot more.
I think it is as much as 10-15 times the amount the impelle "pumps"
comments.author: anode505

comments.text: "bladeless" is the official name for these kind of fans. But yes, an impeller still has small blades.

title: T-800 terminator arm with wrist movement

description.text:
i found the original file http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:645914 on thingiverse.

I remixed some parts.
The fingers can make ad- & abduction movement.
The wrist can flex know. And with the spring loaded pistons it will return in its original position.
The hand pistons are not spring loaded. These rods are made from 2mm aluminium rods

I made a new elbow piece, the arm can now pro and suprinate. If you already printed the "old" version. I have included an adapter piece for the elbow connector.
The upper arm and elbow are movable in flexion an extension. The upper arm will be fitted with a shoulder part.

This is NOT a full replica. Just an attempt for me to get acquainted with 3d printing and modeling.

This is still a work in progress.

Using repetiere and slicer, gives no problems. It will slice the parts even if they are not manifold. However other slicers may find the parts difficult to slice. If you encounter such a problem, please contact me. so i can try to adjust the files.

uploaded more files including sketch up

---UPDATE---------
I uploaded the missing parts. The shoulder top part and the upper arm cover stl.

Printer Brand:

Deltaprintr

Printer:

Deltaprintr Kit

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

30%

Notes:

The most parts are printable without support.
The finger tips where printed with support.

The "old" elbow needs support.

building tips

The 3 small pistons, can/must be fitted with springs. So they can be pushed in, and will return to its position.
Take the outer part.
Insert a spring.
Place the piston part in the outer part.
Place another spring on the piston.
Slide the piston cap on top, to close the outer part. If nessesary, you can shorten the inner piston part. I glued this cap.
Then glue the 2 parts on top of the pistonrod. Use the balplate for calibration of the right depth. When they are to deep and the bal can't move. you can use a washer to gain the right depth. To shallow an d you don't have material left to be bent around the connection balls of the handplat

The large piston, will be to tall. I left it this size, because the length is depending on the springs used for the small pistons.
I had to cut off a small section. Then glue the top, to the piston.

The piston ends will fitt snug to the piston balls (handpart). To make them hold on. I heated the top of the piston ends and bend these to the inside. So they follow the contoure off the pistonballs.

The second handpart is glued on top off the part with the balls.

The upper arm can be bolted together. Before you place the upper arm connector rod. Place the shoulder connector first.

I have uploaded the anterior piston, the alignment is not 100%. I am trying to fix this. This gives no problems at building. But the inner piston will hit grind the piston cap a little bit.

Shoulder part 1a fits in shoulder connector. Make sure the bold witch connects the shoulder connector is NOT to long. Otherwise the shoulder part 1a will not move. Push shoulder part 1b through the gap of the combined shoulder parts. When this part is placed. And rotates fine, glue the endcap (shoulderpart c 2x) on each side..

comments.text:
The larger end on the hand pistons where on the uploaded file deleted, because they were a non manifold. At that time i didn't know how to correct this :). Therefore i removed them. I didn't make a particular part for this. You can download the Sketchup file i included, so you can try make this part yourself. If you not familiar with sketchup, reply me and i will make a stl for you.
The aluminium parts of the hand cylinder are just plane cut. Large enough to make them look like they are proper connected.
For the thumb part, the length is correct. However this part (2 cylinder) was also a non manifold and was giving problems during slicing/printing. I redraw the part, and has only one cylinder now.
Hopefully this helps you to complete the build.

This mould takes defrosted frozen puff pastry squares.
Flour bottom mould and underside of one square, place in mould.
Brush edges with water or milk,
Spoon in sweet or savoury filling,
Flour top mould and topside of another square and place on top.
Line up top half of mould and push down hard - to form the crimps and cut the excess pastry off.
Pull excess pastry away from corners.
Remove top mould carefully (should come straight off if you've floured enough).
Invert and bang lower mould on baking tray - should pop out if floured enough.
Cook.
Eat.
Say "yum yum" or "Ouch" if you didn't let it cool enough.
Make more.

title: MK8 i3 - 50mm Radial Direct Fan Shroud
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The new version of my 50mm radial direct fan shroud that should improve cooling even more with the 50mm radial fan. The model has been designed for the metal carrier of the GEEETech i3 model printers.

There are 4 models included,
1; The standard direct model for the metal carrier with MK8 extruder and hot-end.
2; A direct model designed with a ring holder for a 12mm auto bed level sensor.
3; A direct model designed with a ring holder for a 18mm auto bed level sensor.
4; A 18mm sensor version with a slightly smaller opening tab for slightly smaller radial fans.

The model in the picture was printed with a 0,3mm nozzle, 25mm/s, 35% infill and the fan is being held in place by friction.

For the inductive sensor you can use these settings in Marlin for the bed leveling(actual settings may very depending on machine setup);
[18mm sensor]
X-Offset = -25
Y-Offset = -35

The Z-Offset depends on the mounting height of your sensor on the mount.
Mine is -1.0

Remember to mount your sensor on the fan shroud before you mount the fan shroud, otherwise it might not fit.

Fan position
At the request of jmaurin I have resized the 18mm sensor version so that it will accept a slightly smaller size radial fan, still 50mm but there seems to be a small deviation between all fans.

GEEETech i3 Pro B Metal

If you have any requests about the parts, send me a message

After designing my first fan shroud that fits these printers using a 50mm radial fan, I starting testing using more narrow and direct fan flow to have an increased airflow directed on the nozzle and part.

Print it with buildplate support or manual support, otherwise it will block the airduct channel.

Imported my previous lead holder design (from my Extech 330 meter holder project) from 123D Design into Fusion 360. Created the "sidecar" clip holder and attached it to previous design via the arch bridge. Sliced in Simplify 3D, printed at 60mm/sec on my Sindoh 3Dwox using PLA.

• Nozzle and Extrusion width = 0.4mm
  • Top Layers = 3
  • Bottom Layers = 5 (solid bottom)
  • Wall Thickness = 1.6mm
  • Inner Walls = 2
  • Outer Walls = 2
  • PLA

Print "standing up" in normal use orientation. I did NOT use any supports with slight quality challenges at the top of the knockout circles and one strand of plastic hanging under the arch from bridging which left a small inconsequential void as shown in the photo. (You may want to use a custom support under the arch to avoid this). I wanted my bottom solid so I used 5 layers which resulted in no infill. Using 2 outer and 2 inner walls at 0.4mm/each give you solid walls at 1.6mm with no infill.

I printed this a bit faster than usual at 60mm/sec on my Sindoh 3Dwox instead of the suggestion 40mm/sec default and didn't really see any adverse effects. The slight layer shifting is much more noticeable on the photos than IRL, but my bed screws were also a little loose which caused this.

description.text:
It's summer time! Make the fun game of beersbee for around $10 with printed tops and a couple parts from your local hardware store. Pieces collapse for easy storage and travel.

Parts Required:
2x Printed Beersbee toppers
1x Schedule 40 PVC Conduit – 1/2 In ($4.5 CAD) https://www.homedepot.ca/en/home/p.schedule-40-pvc-conduit--12-in.1000101192.html
2x Schedule 40 PVC Female Adapter – 1/2 Inch ($0.59CAD)
https://www.homedepot.ca/en/home/p.schedule-40-pvc-female-adapter--12-inch.1000100870.html
2x Schedule 40 PVC Male Terminal Adapter – 1/2 Inch ($0.59CAD)
https://www.homedepot.ca/en/home/p.schedule-40-pvc-male-terminal-adapter--12-inch.1000100884.html
1x piece of rebar OR 2x Nail Spikes, test fit the nail head to the PVC in store ($1.05-5.36 CAD)
https://www.homedepot.ca/en/home/p.10m-epoxy-rebar---3-feet.1000115267.html
https://www.homedepot.ca/en/home/p.12spiral-hot-galv-50lb.1000683264.html

Instructions:
Cut the PVC pipe into four 2' sections (61cm)
Alternately, cut them into two 4' sections if you don't want to make the collapsible
Use ABS glue to attach the female couplers to two pieces and the two male couplers to the other two
Attach the beersbee toppers to the empty end of either the male or female sections (glue them on if the fit is loose)
If using rebar, cut the rebar in 12"/30cm pieces with an angled tip
Test fit the rebar spike and wrap a couple sections of electrical tape around it to provide a snug, but easily attachable fit
If using nail spikes, make two wraps of electrical tape similar to the rebar. However, you will need many more wraps to get a good fit to the inside of the PVC

Frisbee and beer not included. Please beersbee responsibly. ;)

I needed a video camera teleprompter recently and (unbelievably!) did not find one already on Thingiverse (as of July 9th, 2016), so had to cobble one up quickly. I'm sharing it here for anyone who needs something like this.

This was quickly designed for my specific needs so please don't complain that it doesn't do this or that. If you need something else, please modify it or design it yourself.

Some notes:

  • The ipad arms and camera risers are mirrored, so just print two of each
  • The glass is 10" x 8" and was appropriated from a picture frame. In my case, the glass was 2.25mm thick. I placed 3M blue tape around the perimeter of the glass initially to protect from sharp edges, but ended up printing up some protective edges for the glass. I left the tape in place as it allows for a better grip, especially for the hinges.
  • The glass is just a press fit onto the hinge, so only install it when you are ready to use it. It can fall off if you are not careful.
  • The ipad holder is sized for an iPad 2 with no case but should allow everything else to sit in place, except maybe an original iPad 1
  • The camera risers are designed to be glued into the slots on the base. I used 2 part epoxy glue
  • The tripod mount is a Manfrotto quick release style specifically for my tripod. It may or may not work for you. It is screwed and glued onto the base. I may add some other mounts later on, or you can design your own. ** Update - I added a mount that accepts a tripod screw, but I did not test it. I'm not sure it's strong enough to hold the whole contraption on the tripod, so use at your own risk.
  • Try to balance your camera and ipad in such a way that the tripod mount is the center of gravity. 3-D PLA printed stuff is not that strong, especially with the grain, and can easily break if too much weight is applied.
  • Everything else is screwed together with #6-32 screws cut to length, except for the hinges, which use #10-32 wingnuts and studs. The camera tripod screw is a 1/4"-20 screw. You can probably find a 1/4-20 wingnut stud but I used what I had around, which was a screw, so you need a screwdriver to tighten.
  • The hinge wing nuts are not positioned in the best way for tightening with the glass in place, so I suggest you use Loctite and tighten them before inserting the glass in place.
  • Ideally, you should cover the glass and camera with a black cloth, but if your background is dark and you turn up the brightness on the ipad you may be able to get away without it.

** 7/11/2016 - Added Manfrotto round mount for Compact Action tripod

I am an undergraduate engineering researcher who was tasked with finding applications for 3D printers. Because of my interest in chemical and mechanical engineering, I decided to look where the two disciplines converge---pumps. This design is an updated version of a previous design.

The main problem with my previous design was leaking. So this design accommodate for that with no adhesives or sealants.

The design works best with 12 mm diameter, flexible tubing for the inlet and outlet.

I used zip ties to hold the assembly together.

For testing I used a 12 V DC hobby motor with a 5 mm drive shaft. I'll be sure to include the motor housing stl however I highly recommend designing a custom motor housing specific for whatever motor you want to use.

With my set up, I was able to push water up >110 cm.

Seal the pump at the motor shaft insert with Vaseline or petroleum jell to minimize leakage.

Printer:

Markforged Mark One

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

50%

description.text: One day I looked at my computer and thought, how can I make this meta? I decided putting a "computer inside of a computer" would be enough. This is a Raspberry Pi 3 Case that fits inside of a 5.25" drive bay. It follows the CD drive standards so it should fit in any computer case with drive bays. The only tested case is an Antec 900.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

This was designed so it doesn't need supports if printed how the model is already positioned. It should be sitting on the face.

Put the Pi on the Mount

Attach the Raspberry Pi to the mount. The case was designed to allow M2.5 screws but I have not tested that. I can confirm that Zip ties do work. Put your preferred attaching method through the mounting holes on the Pi and mount.

Put the Mount in the Case

Attach the HDMI and power wire to the Pi. I would recommend to loop the power wire around the mount, as seen in the below picture, in case the Pi becomes unattached from the mount when plugging something into it. This should prevent the Pi from flying around your PC case and damaging stuff. Next, slide the Pi into your case. You can use M3 screws to secure the Mount into your case as seen below.

I was able to route the cables out the back of the case. Another option is to connect the Pi to a 5v molex line and SSH into it so the entire system is contained inside the PC case.

1. I used Autodesk Inventor to model a drive bay cover based off of these schematics.
    ftp://ftp.seagate.com/sff/SFF-8551.PDF
  2. I created the Pi mount from this model
  3. I 3D printed it and made changes to create a finished mount.

comments.text: Combine this with the RAMPS mounts for 3.5" drive bays, MOSFET mounts for 3.5" bays etc and you could pretty much build all the brains for your printer into the case and save on a power supply... or just protect the electronics from overheating in an enclosed printer without needing a case for them. Octoprint on the pi, 7" LCD on the side of your case?
comments.author: DataBanks

comments.text: I had been contemplating putting a pi inside my tower before but never got beyond the "it would be cool" idea. Now I'm thinking of how to embed a monitor on the side to plug into the pi. I guess you could add sensors to the pi to keep track of stuff inside, but i like the idea of a virtual fish tank, or screensaver, or maybe a standalone music or video player that won't lag the PC while I'm doing other stuff.

description.text:
This is still a work in progress and all your help is needed.
I'm trying to accomplish:

  • Biggest build volume for about 1500 €
  • Multi tool able, like CNC
  • All parts metal
  • Easy sourcing of parts

There will be updates soon.

It will be made from normal square aluminium profile, some parts might be printable and the corners can be hand made, but a cnc would be the best option.

It is ready. Well it prints amazing quality prints. It's now in use, and it's printing my main project. I didn't make the 3D file complete, or the aesthetics to the top notch. It CNC machines wood too, but for metal it would need a screw driven axis.

24.7.2017 - The feedrate problem was solved. The issue was the stepperdrivers which has a different kind of factor system than the 3D printers usually have. The dimenssion are only 145016901600. The Z height will be better when I get my cable chains. But now it's working. The Nema23 where a big pain to configure, because the Internet forums where misguiding alot!

21.7.2017 - It's now ready without the heated bed. I only have one problem that the movement feedrate is too slow :( .

26.6.2017 - The printer is almost complete, but the build volume is just 1700x1500x1700mm. It's only missing the heater parts. I got it moving with the drivers. Now it's a waiting game :) After when it's done I will send solidworks files that who ever can use them as they like.

18.4.2017 - The printer's Z-axxis and program is now ready. I need now to mount the XY axxis, which is ready. BUT I have to delay the project for 1 month (WORK). I think the hardest thing is now done, and I only need to do some wiring and calibrations. NEW PICTURES.

16.4.2017 - The new enclosure's drivers and PSU's where installed. The Z-motors are now installed with the rods. Hopefully I will get to try and calibrate the Z-movenet, which is the most hardest with this printer. I'm planning to get the device's Z-axis done on 17.4.2017.

19.3.2017 - The printer needed 8 pcs Nema23 motors. An order of new drivers, bigger enclosure and motors where made. Maybe in 2 weeks I will have the printer moving on XYZ.

11.3.2017 - Calibration of the z-axxis is done. Now installing lift screws and XY-components.

14.2.2017 - I have installed the guide rails, all except one (I made the hole too big). And I uploaded a true world picture, just for you fan boys out there ;)

10.1.2017 - I have made the structure, and it was a HUGE work. It is stable but I noticed that the z-axxis needs to have adjustment screws or something to have the best quality. This adjustment I haven't seen in any printer, but this size needs it a lot.

6,9,2016 - I have ordered all the metal parts and I'm making the frame. And I have some thoughts that I might not make it as corexy, but I will see. NEMA 23 is expensive, so corexy would be great.

25,7,2016 - The Z-axis motors will be on the top, because the heated bed would heat the z-axis belts.

author: ridercz

title: The Makerbot Adjustable Cubicle Coat Hook

description.text:
UPDATED:  Note that the design has been updated on 2/1/12.  The improved design has proven much more reliable and sturdy than the original.  Pictures of the finished product will replace the outdated first rivision shown.
This is a project long in the making.  This was one of the very first things I thought of to make if I ever got a MakerBot.  No one has coat hooks but plenty of coats. In my office these things are so rare you'd think you have to win them off a terrible Dread Office Supply Clerk in an epic boss battle.  This in turn leads to a lot of rather interesting substitutions involving duct-tape and paper clips.  
But I thought I could improve on that a bit.  So here it is, an Adjustable MakerBot Cubicle Coat Hook. 
I designed it with everyone in mind.  I designed it to use 10-32-1/2" Screws with 3/8" nuts.  These should be easy to find.  I further chose the screws with the flat or Phillips head so there's bound to be a way to tighten it in the office.  I also made the back stop adjustable so that it can be moved and secured to any size cubicle wall.
I'm really happy with the way this turn out.  And I think it looks pretty slick too. Plus I think it could be used for other great things like, holding hats, hanging plants, and small orangutans who have inexplicably found they're way into your office and need a good hook to hang on to.
I hope my fellow cubicle drones can make great use of this.

UPDATED: 2/1/12 (I tested this design this morning. A couple of notes. One is that with the increased dimensions the part dows print over almost all of the y-axis, so be sure that your position is well calibrated. Also The support stuck into the 'M' on the backstop a little more intrusively this time and was a little more difficult ot remove. However, the big result was that I'm calling this design a success. The teeth on the back were a huge improvement and held into the cubicle wall nicely. I will likely test the weight capacity at lunch, but from I would estimate that it would hold at least 40 lbs! So this is a huge improvement over what we currently have) UPDATED: 1/31/12 (I added a stiffer backstop and teeth on the interior of the backstop. I also added a fillet to the backstop to reduce the stress concentration there. I increased the added more material to the inside of the hook for extra strength. I also added a forward block to reduce the bending moment created by the force on the hook.)

  • Choose the appropriate .stl file. I have one for black ABS and one of white. (These are the only two colors of ABS I've used so far, so the drawings may have to be adjusted a bit to accommodate for different contraction rates for the different ABS colors.)

  • Generate the Gcode in ReplicatorG, using full support. (I suppose int he future I might consider splitting the main body in half to make it easier to print, but full support works fine.)

  • CARFULLY remove the rafting from the two pieces using an Exacto knife. (Please be careful it is really easy to cut yourself with this stuff. The battle scars on my fingers are why I where gloves in all my photos. So be careful.)

  • (Optional) Fill the MakerBot logo with red paint. For this I used an old trick I learned while restoring vintage boat motors, and that is to use a syringe WITH THE TIP GROUND OFF to inject the paint into small holes. (Please note if you ask for syringes from you local drug store it can be a little degrading, so be aware.)
    • Also this method comes with a BIG warning. Before you grind the tip off the syringe it is VERY sharp, so be careful not to stick yourself, you could get into a lot of trouble that way. And don't even think about not grinding the tip off. You do this for two reason. First a sharp metal thing and paint don't mix comprende. Some how I don't imagine paint int he bloodstream is going to end well. Second if you don't grind the point off the paint is going to squirt out the side and just make a mess.

  • Install the hardware. You'll need 2 each 10/32-1/2" machine screws in what ever head type you like, and two each 3/8" nuts in 10/32 threading. Load the nuts into the bottom of the backstop and the screws go on top of the slotted main body.

  • Then just adjust and tighten the screws to the desired wall thickness and viola you have one handsome looking cube coat hook.

description.text:
Edit 2/14/17: part files have been updated. many small adjustments have been made to improve the quality of this puzzle. There is also a .zip file added that contains a set of alternate parts to create a fully proportional 3x3x5.

Video of it here showing solve. Last few minutes show some internals.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HTi-uVYUPYc

This is a 3x3x5 puzzle cube. You will need to provide your own core and screws/springs from another cube. I recommend using a YJ Guanlong core, as these can be found for $3-4 and this has been designed with that core.

Surfaces will need to be sanded smooth to allow best operation of the cube, and to allow the stickers to adhere properly to the sides. It takes some work to get this working properly.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

Mini

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

15-20%

Notes:

I do extensive sanding to my puzzles, so I print at standard quality for speed.

This puzzle will require extensive sanding to get it working properly. If it's not turning well, you most likely need to sand more.

I use a combination of sandpapers from 180 grit on up to 1500 grit for my puzzles. It is a lot of work, but if you can still see printed lines, you haven't gone far enough.

I do all my work with Open Source software.

This puzzle was designed exclusively in Blender 3D.

I use OpenSCAD and no matter what I do I can't get it to render with your center piece imported. What software did you use to model these parts?

comments.text: The core will fit, but The screws for sails are a bit longer so the puzzle may be a bit loose. The really good news is that only one piece needs to be adjusted if it doesn't fit (The inner center), and that piece is common to all my puzzles here.

comments.text: What would I do to adjust it? Would I cut down the centers, extend them, or something else?
comments.author: rcpongo

comments.text: It really depends on the core and hardware you are using. A Sail should be very close to working, but it may be just a bit loose due to the longer screws. In that case all you would have to do is shorten the spring section of the center piece. I'd say go ahead and print it, and then see if you have an issue. I don't mind remaking a few pieces for you if needed because I really need to come up with a new center anyways, since Guanlongs have changed.

title: Fully Customisable Power supply Endcap... yep another

description.text:
Well it be another end cap for those power supplys everyone is so fond of. Didnt like the ones I saw so made my own. It's fully customisable... well as far as I could think to make it. It specifically setup for a switch/ kettle plug combo I got with the one i purchased. UPDATE:-
So after having this installed, I found that it needed nut captions to hold them in place. As such I ended up using rivets. Issue with this is that it didn't hold well enough and pulled loose. I have made version 2 with 2 slots added to hold nuts. Only uploaded scad file at this stage, as measurements of slots not fine tuned yet. you will need to set these dimensions to the correct dimensions of the nut being used.

measure everything. enter into scad file and print the result.  
You will need 2 bolts that will fit through teh slots in the side oft eh power supply.  
make sure the height of the terminal block is set just high enough to clear any components really close to the metal on either side.  
depth will need to be adjusted to make sure there is no shorting.  
the rest is pretty self explanitory.

The 3d printed shoe itself, with the epoxy I used is pretty sturdy, but please be sure test it out and use at your own risk if you plan to actually wear the shoes.

The shoes were designed for a 3d printed gown. You can find more info on the project here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1664748

title: Rachio Gen2 LED logo sliding cover

description.text:
We have installed our Gen2 Rachio in our bathroom which unfortunately has no door between the bathroom and our master bedroom. The blue Rachio logo LED indicator is very bright and lights up the whole bathroom at night.

At first I tried covering it with black electrical tape, which completely blocks out all light from the LED indictor. This was good first solution, but I wanted to sometimes be able to see the status of the Rachio system.

Then I decided to try using white electrical so that some of the light from the LED would pass through but also appear more dimly. I applied multiple layers of tape which certainly dimmed the LED and made it darker in our bathroom/bedroom. It was possible to view the LED read out through the tape, but we decided it was still too bright at night even after adding 3 or 4 layers of white tape.

Finally, I tried 3D modeling a sliding plastic cover that slips across the whole face of the Rachio Gen 2 unit vertically. It covered the LED logo circle area and a little bit more. It can be slid back and forth across the front and expose or cover the LED on demand. I am still making improvements to the design and would love feedback from other users. I will post the Solidworks native file as well as an .STL file for anyone who wants to print it out as is. If you make improvement on your own or have suggested changes, please post them here. or contact me at @jellenbogen on Twitter.

The photos currently included are of an early prototype used for initial designing and checking measurements. The STL and Solidworks files (and 3D model preview) are the latest version as of 7/9/16.

Not really sure what these are called, and the best name I could come up with was an "Oreo Spoon".
These little utincils hold an Oreo in the hook for dunking in milk, and the holder can hold up to four Oreo spoons if for some reason you decide to share your Oreos with someone.

You can print the Oreo spoons whole, or have the hook and handle separate, and then glue them together.

NOTE ON FOOD SAFETY

Be sure to print with plastics that are food safe, and non-toxic. Luckily, PLA and ABS are mostly harmless. See this article: https://pinshape.com/blog/3d-printing-food-safe/
Even with a non-toxic plastic, to prevent bacteria buildup, you should use some kind of food grade sealant or resin. Personally, I use this: https://www.amazon.com/Claphams-Beeswax-870-3008-Finish-8-Ounces/dp/B0012XP7LQ/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1468104809&sr=8-2&keywords=salad+bowl+finish
Also, you shouldn't put them in the dishwasher, as I don't know how the plastic will react to the heat.

description.text:
Airfoil section intended for hybrid construction (combining 3D printed components with foam, wood, fiberglass, etc.). Simple wing rib which is intended to be mounted on a supporting spar with another material stretched or glued over it.

This is not based on any specific NACA profile, but should be able to get lift if used as part of the structure when building a wing. (Has the general airfoil profile and larger lift surface on top.) Intended for a mix n' match type project, where a generic wing may be handy.

Blend file isn't to any specific scale, so feel free to edit for size.

I was thinking to try to make a PLA rib to replace a balsa rib and cover the wing with monocote film. Density of PLA is about 10 times that of balsa, but tensile strength is about 3.6 times balsa. title: Aeronaut Folding Prop Stop insert
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
First a BIG thanks to Noircogi, an RCGroups poster, for his own prop stop idea that inspired my design!

For those that want to use a folding prop in a pusher configuration, this piece might help. It is designed to replace two stop plates with a one piece insert to fit an Aeronaut 38mm folding propeller yoke. The parts function is to stop the blades from extending too far and striking the plane as well as stopping the blades from crossing each other when folded (over-folding).

The advantage to this one piece insert is it is light, it doesn't take up as much space on the propeller shaft and it is much easier to set-up and balance.

There are three STL files for three different prop shaft sizes - 5mm, 6mm and 8mm.

UPDATE #1: I have changed the profile a bit to fit a wider selection of props. I have also added two inserts for the 42mm Yoke size.

UPDATE #2: I have added a 42mm x 5mm size.

For more information on my pusher set-up please visit the project page here:

http://www.itsqv.com/QVM/index.php?title=How_To_-_Set-Up_a_Pusher_Style_Folding_Prop#3D_Printed_Insert
